  "prompt": "College and NCAA Football: (NFL) In overtime, is the kicking team allowed to do an onside kick and if successful does the other team get the ball afterwards?",
  "response": "In the NFL, during overtime, the team that receives the kickoff has the first opportunity to possess the ball. The kicking team (the team that does not initially get possession) can indeed attempt an onside kick\u2014just as they can in regulation play. If the kicking team successfully recovers the onside kick, they would gain possession of the ball.\n\nHowever, possession rules in overtime are slightly different from regulation play. If the team that receives the onside kick (originally the kicking team) scores a field goal on their ensuing possession, the game proceeds and the opposing team will have an opportunity to possess the ball and either tie the game with a field goal or win with a touchdown. If the receiving team scores a touchdown, the game ends immediately. Similarly, if the receiving team (via the onside kick) does not score, the opposing team still gets a chance to possess the ball.\n\nIn summary, if the kicking team successfully recovers an onside kick in overtime, they gain possession and continue their drive until they score or turn the ball over, adhering to the rules of overtime possession.",
